    <prompt id="1">What is a computer?</prompt>
    <prompt id="2">What is computer programming?</prompt>
    <prompt id="3">What is the internet?</prompt>
    <prompt id="4">What is a computer network?</prompt>
    <prompt id="5">What is a router?</prompt>
    <prompt id="6">What is a modem?</prompt>
    <prompt id="7">What is an ISP?</prompt>
    <prompt id="8">What is an IP Address?</prompt>
    <prompt id="9">What is a domain name?</prompt>
  </prompts>



  <responses>
    <response id="1">A computer is a computing / information processing device.</response>
    <response id="2">Computer programming is the process of composing and organizing a collection of instructions. These instructions tell a computer/software program what to do in a language that the computer understands. These instructions come in the form of many different languages such as JavaScript, HTML and Rust.</response>
    <response id="3">The Internet is a large network of computers that communicate together. It began in the 1960s as a US-army-funded research project and then evolved into a public infrastructure in the 1980s with the support of many public universities and private companies.</response>
    <response id="4">A computer network is group of communicating computers, connected via cables, Wi-Fi or Bluetooth.</response>
    <response id="5">A router is a computer that knows how to forward messages between networks.</response>
    <response id="6">Modems help us connect routers b/c a modem turns router information into information that can transport telephone infrastructure.</response>
    <response id="7">Modems help us connect computers via telephone lines.</response>
    <response id="8">An ISP (Internet Service Provider) is a company that manages special routers. All ISP Routers are linked together &amp; all internet traffic flow through ISP's.</response>
    <response id="9">An IP (Internet Protocol) address is an address made of a series of four numbers separated by dots (example: 192.0.2.172). Any computer linked to a network has a unique IP address that identifies it. To reach a computer over the internet we may use its IP Address but b/c numbers are harder to remember then a name we alias IP Addresses w/ domain names.</response>
    <response id="10">We can alias an IP address with a human-readable name called a domain name. For example (at the time of writing; IP addresses can change) google.com is the domain name used on top of the IP address 142.250.190.78. Using the domain name is the easiest way for us to reach a computer over the Internet.</response>
  </responses>



